@NODE Intro "Introduction to ScriptLauncher"

ScriptLauncher is a very configurable program launcher which allows you to
create one or more windows of buttons which can run AmigaDOS scripts. Each
button in each window is associated with a script that can do anything AmigaDOS
commands allow.

You can change just about every aspect of each window and its buttons,
including:

  -  The number of @{"rows, columns, & orientation" LINK Dims} of buttons
  -  The @{"sizes" LINK BSIZE} of the buttons (all buttons of a window are the same size)
  -  Each button's @{"colors" LINK Color}
  -  Each button's @{"label" LINK Button}
  -  The @{"fonts" LINK Font} used for button labels
  -  The AmigaDOS @{"script" LINK Button} that each button runs
  -  The @{"public screen" LINK Screen} the windows appear on
  -  Each window's @{"position" LINK Window} on the screen
  -  Margins @{"between" LINK Bspace} and @{"around" LINK Margin} the buttons
  -  Each window's @{"background color" LINK Wbkgd}

ScriptLauncher uses a text configuration file to specify these parameters.

You can also set up multiple @{"pages" LINK Page} of buttons. ScriptLauncher allows you to
define up to 20 pages of buttons for each window. You can move from one page
to another, and you can set up a button to @{"jump" LINK CmdPage} to a specific page.

As of version 1.1, ScriptLauncher can now open multiple windows of buttons, each of
which may be more than one page in length. The first window defined is the main
window and is always opened when ScriptLauncher is run. Any additional windows
can be opened either at startup or on demand using the @{"=OPENWIN" link Openwin} script command.

		       @{b}@{u}The Theory Behind ScriptLauncher@{ub}@{uu}

First you define the @{"fonts" link Font} and custom @{"colors" LINK Color} you'd like to use, then you define
one or more @{"types" LINK Type} of buttons. Each type of button will have its own colors,
allowing you to make groups of buttons that share a similar feature. For example,
you might define a button type called "APP" that represents your major
applications, or a button type called "GAME". All the "APP" buttons will be
colored the same way, and so will all the "GAME" buttons.

After defining your button types, you can define @{"buttons" LINK Button} of each particular
type. Each button's label or tag will be different, and each button will have
an individual AmigaDOS script associated with it. All buttons of the same
type will appear with the same colors. They don't have to be physically
grouped together, but it looks nicer that way. :)
@ENDNODE

@NODE Dist "How ScriptLauncher is distributed"

ScriptLauncher is freely distributable, and is (c) @{"Joe Howard" LINK Author}. It must
be distributed unchanged and complete with its documentation file.
ScriptLauncher is distributed as-is, without warranty of any kind. You are
not allowed to make any profit if you redistribute ScriptLauncher.

At this point in the Amiga's history (2005), with the likes of YAM and AWeb
as freely distributable programs, I can't see charging a shareware fee for
most noncommercial Amiga software that's written. The Amiga needs new software
at this point and this is my small contribution to it.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Require "ScriptLauncher's Requirements"

ScriptLauncher requires at least update #1 of OS4.0 and is a native PPC
program. It has no requirements beyond what is included in the basic OS.

Before running ScriptLauncher, you must construct a configuration file
for it, which describes the layout and contents of the buttons it will
create in its windows.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Install "ScriptLauncher Installation"

ScriptLauncher installation is as simple as copying the executable
to whatever drawer you want it in, such as C: or WBStartup.

ScriptLauncher comes with a small sample configuration file that you can
use as a base for creating your own file from. I also (hopefully) have set
it up so that it will run "out of the box" on OS4 systems if you just want
try it out first. The sample file has comments in so you can follow what
the various commands are for.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Exec "Starting ScriptLauncher"

You can start ScriptLauncher from either the Shell or Workbench.


     @{"Shell Startup" LINK ExecShell}

     @{"Workbench Startup" LINK ExecWB}

@ENDNODE

@NODE ExecShell "ScriptLauncher Shell Startup"

ScriptLauncher takes one optional parameter when started from the Shell:

    @{b}ScriptLauncher [configfilename]@{ub}

where

    configfilename  is the name of the configuration file to use. It should
		    either be in the current directory or be fully qualified.
		    If this file is not specified, or if it is not found,
		    ScriptLauncher will look for a file "ScriptLauncher.config"
		    in PROGDIR: first, then if that is not found, in the current
		    directory, and if that is not found, it will look in S:.
@ENDNODE

@NODE ExecWB "ScriptLauncher Workbench Startup"

ScriptLauncher takes one optional tooltype when started from Workbench:

    @{b}FILE=configfilename

    CONFIG=configfilename@{ub}

Either FILE or CONFIG may be specified as the tooltype.

where

    configfilename  is the name of the configuration file to use. It should
		    either be in the current directory or be fully qualified.
		    If this file is not specified, or if it is not found,
		    ScriptLauncher will look for a file "ScriptLauncher.config"
		    in PROGDIR: first, then if that is not found, in the current
		    directory, and if that is not found, it will look in S:.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Usage "Using ScriptLauncher"

Here we describe how to use ScriptLauncher once you have set up a valid
configuration file and started ScriptLauncher. You can....

	    @{"   Use buttons you've created   " LINK UseButton}

	    @{"   Display other button pages   " LINK UsePage}

	    @{"   Use ScriptLauncher menus     " LINK UseMenu}

	    @{"   Modify scripts               " LINK UseMod}

	    @{"   Quit ScriptLauncher          " LINK UseQuit}
@ENDNODE

@NODE UseButton "Using buttons you've created"

Most of the time, you will use ScriptLauncher by simply clicking on the
buttons you have set up. ScriptLauncher will run the script associated
with each button. A script will not have an output window unless you
have specified an @{"output spec" LINK Button} for the button. Each button can have a
different output spec.

Warning - make sure you don't @{b}double-click@{ub} ScriptLauncher's buttons. They are
intended to be single clicked. If you accidentally double-click one, it will
probably run the button's script twice!

ScriptLauncher copies the script, with possible overrides, to a file in T:
called "ScriptLauncher.nnnn", where "nnnn" starts at 0000 and is incremented
by 1 until it finds a file that is not in use. ScriptLauncher cannot know
when the script is finished running, so it does not delete the script files
from T:. You the user, however, can clean up the T: directory any time by
doing:

    delete T:ScriptLauncher#?

All script files that are finished will be deleted; those that are still
running will have a lock on the file and will not be deleted.
@ENDNODE

@NODE UsePage "Displaying other button pages"

If you have defined more than one page of buttons for a window, you can advance
from one page to another by one of three means:

      -  use the @{"Next page" LINK UseMenu} and @{"Previous page" LINK UseMenu} menu items

      -  click the middle mouse button (if you have one), which will advance
	 you to the next page

      -  set up a button to execute the @{"=PAGE" LINK CmdPage} script command which can move
	 you forward, backward, or to a specific page of buttons.
@ENDNODE

@NODE UseMenu "Using ScriptLauncher menu items"

ScriptLauncher has six menu items in its Project menu:

@{b}@{u}Next page@{ub}@{uu}

This menu item will display the next page of buttons for the current window,
if you have defined more than one page. If you are already displaying the
last page, it will wrap around to page 1.

@{b}@{u}Previous page@{ub}@{uu}

This menu item will display the previous page of buttons for the current window,
if you have defined more than one page. If you are already displaying the
first page, it will wrap around to the last page.

@{b}@{u}About@{ub}@{uu}

This menu item will show a brief requester about ScriptLauncher including its
version number and release date.

@{b}@{u}Reopen main window@{ub}@{uu}

This menu item is ghosted if the main window is already open. If the main window
is closed, the item is unghosted and allows you to reopen the main window.

@{b}@{u}Restart@{ub}@{uu}

This menu item will restart ScriptLauncher execution. All open windows will
be closed, the configuration file will be read in again, and a new window(s)
of buttons will be opened. You will typically use this when you have updated
the configuration file and want to put it into effect.

@{b}@{u}Quit@{ub}@{uu}

This menu item will quit ScriptLauncher.

@ENDNODE

@NODE UseMod "Modifying scripts"

Each line of a button's script (except for script command lines) can be
@{b}modified@{ub} by shift-clicking the button. This will cause ScriptLauncher to
open a requester window allowing you to modify each script line individually.
In the override window, you have four options:

  - Click @{b}OK@{ub} or hit @{b}ENTER@{ub} to include this line in the script. You can change it
    if you wish. If you want to eliminate a line of a script, either prefix it
    with a ";" to turn it into a comment to AmigaDOS, or erase the line in the
    string gadget entirely.

  - Click @{b}"Run script"@{ub} to make this the last override that will appear. The
    line can be modified as above.

  - Click @{b}"Insert line"@{ub} to insert a new line in the script at the current point.
    The new line will be taken from the string gadget. The original line that is
    in the string gadget will be presented to you again at the next override. See
    below for an example of how to insert lines at different points in a script.

  - Click @{b}"Cancel script"@{ub} or hit @{b}ESC@{ub} to abort running this script entirely.
    ScriptLauncher will delete the temporary file in T: and not execute it
    at all.

You can also force an individual script line to be modified by using the @{"=MOD" LINK CmdMod}
script command, even if you haven't shift-clicked the button. This is useful for
lines that you know you'll always want to modify in some way.

It is also possible to use the @{b}ALT, CTRL,@{ub} and @{b}AMIGA@{ub} keys in clicking buttons.
These keys can be used as modifiers for specific script lines. You can set up
a script to include certain lines only if the button is ALT-clicked, for
example. See @{"=IF" LINK CmdIf} under @{"Script Commands" LINK Scrcmds}.

			 @{b}@{u}Inserting Lines in Scripts@{ub}@{uu}

When you click "Insert line" you are asking ScriptLauncher to insert the contents
of the string gadget @{b}before@{ub} the current line. The following examples show how to
insert lines in the middle of a script, at the beginning of a script, and at the
end of a script.

Let's assume we have a button with the following script:

	-button 'BACKUPS' SHELL con:0/0/574/600/Backups/Close
   (1)  addbuffers dh5: 300
   (2)  execute s:backupDH0
   (3)  execute s:backupDH1

Script line numbers are shown in parentheses for clarity.

@{u}Example 1@{uu} - Adding a line to the middle of a script

Suppose you wished to add the line "info dh5:" before line 2 of this script. The
following chart shows the requester dialog you would use:
@{b}
      String gadget contents	       Replace with		You click@{ub}
	addbuffers dh5: 300	       [no change]		OK
	execute s:backupDH0	       info dh5:		Insert line
	execute s:backupDH0	       [no change]		OK
	execute s:backupDH1	       [no change]		OK

The resultant script is:

	addbuffers dh5: 300
	info dh5:
	execute s:backupDH0
	execute s:backupDH1

@{u}Example 2@{uu} - Adding a line to the start of a script

Suppose you wished to add the line "prompt" before line 1 of this script. The
following chart shows the requester dialog you would use:
@{b}
      String gadget contents	       Replace with		You click@{ub}
	addbuffers dh5: 300	       prompt			Insert line
	addbuffers dh5: 300	       [no change]		OK
	execute s:backupDH0	       [no change]		OK
	execute s:backupDH1	       [no change]		OK

The resultant script is:

	prompt
	addbuffers dh5: 300
	execute s:backupDH0
	execute s:backupDH1

You could also have clicked "Run script" instead of "OK" if you were making no
changes after that point in the script.

@{u}Example 3@{uu} - Adding a line to the end of a script

Suppose you wished to add the line "addbuffers dh5: -300" after line 3 of this
script. The following chart shows the requester dialog you would use:
@{b}
      String gadget contents	       Replace with		You click@{ub}
	addbuffers dh5: 300	       [no change]		OK
	execute s:backupDH0	       [no change]		OK
	execute s:backupDH1	       [no change]		Insert line
	execute s:backupDH1	       addbuffers dh5: -300	OK

The resultant script is:

	addbuffers dh5: 300
	execute s:backupDH0
	execute s:backupDH1
	addbuffers dh5: -300

You can insert as many lines after the last line as you wish by entering them in
the string gadget and clicking "Insert line" for all but the last one.
@ENDNODE

@NODE UseQuit "Quitting ScriptLauncher"

You quit ScriptLauncher by closing all its windows or by selecting the Quit
menu item. ScriptLauncher does not end until the last window is closed. Also,
a button can cause ScriptLauncher to quit by including the @{"=QUIT" LINK CmdQuit} command
in a script.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Config "ScriptLauncher Configuration File Setup"

ScriptLauncher's configuration file is a text file that you must set up
before running ScriptLauncher. By default, this file is named
"ScriptLauncher.config" but can be named anything you want if you specify
the file name when @{"running" LINK Exec} ScriptLauncher. Use your favorite text editor
to set it up.

If you do not specify a configuration file when ScriptLauncher starts up,
ScriptLauncher will look first in PROGDIR:, then in the current directory,
and then in S: for "ScriptLauncher.config". If you do specify a file name
to ScriptLauncher, it can reside in any directory - just give it the full
path name.

ScriptLauncher configuration commands are prefixed with a '-' in column 1.
Command names are case-insensitive. @{"Comments" LINK Comment} may be included in the
configuration file by prefixing the line with '--'. Blank lines may be used
freely in the configuration file.

In the commands that follow, keywords are CAPITALIZED, and parameters that
you must fill in are in lower case. Parameters can be separated by one or
more spaces or tabs. Optional parameters are indicated in [brackets].
Multiple choices are indicated with a vertical bar '|'. Character strings
do not need to be enclosed in quotes unless they contain embedded spaces.
If spaces are embedded, enclose a string in either single ('') or double ("")
quotes.

ScriptLauncher also allows you to specify commands in other files which are
"included" with the @{"-INCLUDE" LINK Include} command. One use of this feature is to separate
the button and script definitions from the other configuration options,
allowing you to have multiple button color schemes without having to define
each button multiple times. Note, however, that nesting of -INCLUDE commands
is not supported.

If a command has a syntax error, ScriptLauncher will notify you of the error
and will not run successfully. The error is shown in a small window and includes
the error message and the specific configuration line where the error occurred
(if possible). Respond either by closing the window or hitting any key.

As of version 1.1 of ScriptLauncher, allowing multiple windows to be defined, the
configuration file has become more complex. Some commands pertain to a single
window being defined and others are global to all windows. Here is the most
logical layout for a typical configuration file:

  - @{b}Global@{ub} commands:			     -SCREEN, -FONT, -COLOR, -TYPE
  ----------------------------------------
  - Attributes for the @{b}main@{ub} or only window:  -WINDOW, -DIMS, -BSIZE, -BSPACE,
  -					     -MARGIN, -BORDER, -WTITLE, -WBKGD
  -
  - Buttons for the main or only window:     -BUTTON, -EMPTY, -NEWROW, -NEWCOL, -PAGE
  ----------------------------------------
  - NEWWIN command for a @{b}second@{ub} window:      -NEWWIN
  -
  - Attributes for a second window:	     -WINDOW, -DIMS, -BSIZE, -BSPACE,
  -	(optional)                           -MARGIN, -BORDER, -WTITLE, -WBKGD
  -
  - Buttons for a second window:	     -BUTTON, -EMPTY, -NEWROW, -NEWCOL, -PAGE
  ----------------------------------------
  - NEWWIN command for a @{b}third@{ub} window:       -NEWWIN
  -
  - Attributes for a third window:	     -WINDOW, -DIMS, -BSIZE, -BSPACE,
  -	(optional)                           -MARGIN, -BORDER, -WTITLE, -WBKGD
  -
  - Buttons for a third window: 	     -BUTTON, -EMPTY, -NEWROW, -NEWCOL, -PAGE
  ----------------------------------------
  - etc. for all windows

Note that you do @{b}not@{ub} specify the -NEWWIN command for the first (main) window.
It is only used to define additional windows. This allows for full compatibility
with V1.0 configuration files. The first window attributes and group of buttons
you define are for the main window. For each additional window, you can repeat
the commands that specify the window attributes. This is optional: each new window
inherits attributes from the preceding window, if they are not specified for the
new window. The only attribute that is not inherited by a new window is the window
title.

The following commands specify items that are global to all windows and do not
pertain to a single window:

   @{"-COLOR  " LINK Color}  Define a color to use
   @{"-FONT   " LINK Font}  Specify a font to use for button labels
   @{"-TYPE   " LINK Type}  Define a type of button
   @{"-SCREEN " LINK Screen}  Specify the public screen to open windows on

   @{"-INCLUDE" LINK Include}  Read another file of configuration commands
   @{"--      " LINK Comment}  Include a comment line

The following commands are specified once for each window to be defined:

   @{"-NEWWIN " LINK Newwin}  Define an additional window (not used for main window)
   @{"-WINDOW " LINK Window}  Window position on screen
   @{"-DIMS   " LINK Dims}  Button orientation, and number of rows and columns
   @{"-BSIZE  " LINK Bsize}  Button size in pixels
   @{"-BSPACE " LINK Bspace}  Spacing between buttons in pixels
   @{"-MARGIN " LINK Margin}  Spacing around buttons in pixels
   @{"-BORDER " LINK Border}  Colors for button edges
   @{"-WTITLE " LINK Wtitle}  Window title
   @{"-WBKGD  " LINK Wbkgd}  Window background color

The following commands are used to lay out buttons on each page of a window:

   @{"-BUTTON " LINK Button}  Define a button and its script
   @{"-EMPTY  " LINK Empty }  Define an empty space
   @{"-NEWROW " LINK Newrow}  Start a new row of buttons
   @{"-NEWCOL " LINK Newcol}  Start a new column of buttons
   @{"-PAGE   " LINK Page}  Start a new page of buttons
@ENDNODE

@NODE Dims "Button orientation, and number of rows and columns"

You can set the numbers of button rows and columns for a window with the
-DIMS command:

    @{b}-DIMS  columns@{ub}  @{b}rows  [VERT|HORIZ]@{ub}

where

    columns  =	The number of columns of buttons.

    rows     =	The number of rows of buttons.

    VERT     =	Lay out buttons vertically, one column after another.
		Typically you would use this if the window has less
		columns than rows. This is the default.

    HORIZ    =	Lay out buttons horizontally, one row after another.
		Typically you might use this if the window has less rows
		than columns.

If no -DIMS command is given for the main window, ScriptLauncher defaults
to 2 columns and 8 rows of buttons, with buttons laid out vertically. If
-DIMS is not specified for a new window, ScriptLauncher uses the previous
window's -DIMS values.

ScriptLauncher will determine the total window size by a combination of
the parameters on the -DIMS, -BSIZE, -BSPACE, and -MARGIN commands.

Examples:

    -DIMS  2 25 VERT	This produces a button window of 2 columns with
			25 buttons in each column. Buttons are filled in
			column by column.

    -DIMS  10 4 HORIZ	This produces a button window of 10 columns with
			4 buttons in each column. Buttons are filled in
			row by row.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Bsize "Button size in pixels"

You can set the size of each button of a window with the -BSIZE command:
@{b}
    -BSIZE  width  height
@{ub}
where

    width    =	The width of one button in pixels. This must be at least 10.

    height   =	The height of one button in pixels. This must be at least 6.

If no -BSIZE command is given for the main window, buttons will be made 90
pixels wide and 15 pixels tall. If -BSIZE is not specified for a new window,
ScriptLauncher uses the previous window's -BSIZE values.

Note: It would be smart to coordinate this command with the @{"-FONT" LINK Font} commands
so that your buttons are big enough to accommodate the labels you give them.
ScriptLauncher will center each button's label in the button horizontally and
vertically. If the button's vertical size is too small for the font to fit,
an error message will be issued.

Example:

    -BSIZE  100 12	All buttons for this window will be 100 pixels wide and
			12 pixels high.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Bspace "Spacing between buttons in pixels"

You can separate buttons by a specific number of pixels with the -BSPACE command:

    @{b}-BSPACE  xgap  ygap@{ub}

where

    xgap  =  The number of pixels between buttons horizontally.

    ygap  =  The number of pixels between buttons vertically.

Space between buttons, if any, is filled with the window's @{"background color" LINK Wbkgd}.

Both parameters default to zero for the main window, meaning that buttons are
laid out next to each other in both dimensions with no intervening space. If
-BSPACE is not specified for a new window, ScriptLauncher uses the previous
window's -BSPACE values.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Margin "Spacing around buttons in pixels"

You can create a margin around a window's buttons with the -MARGIN command:

    @{b}-MARGIN  leftright  topbottom@{ub}

where

    leftright  =  The number of pixels added on the left and right sides
		  of the buttons.

    topbottom  =  The number of pixels added on the top and bottom sides
		  of the buttons.

Button margins, if any, are filled with the window's @{"background color" LINK Wbkgd}.

Both parameters default to zero for the main window, meaning that buttons are
laid out next to the window's borders with no intervening space. If -MARGIN is
not specified for a new window, ScriptLauncher uses the previous window's
-MARGIN values.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Border "Colors for button edges"

You can specify the colors to use for a button's edges with the -BORDER command:

    @{b}-BORDER  shinecolor  shadowcolor@{ub}

where

    shinecolor	  =  The name of the @{"color" LINK Color} to use for a button's "shine" edge.
		     The color must be defined prior to this point.

    shadowcolor   =  The name of the @{"color" LINK Color} to use for a button's "shadow"
		     edge. The color must be defined prior to this point.

Both colors must be specified if -BORDER is used. If -BORDER is not specified for
the main window, ScriptLauncher uses the screen's SHINE and SHADOW pens. If
-BORDER is not specified for a new window, ScriptLauncher uses the previous
window's -BORDER values.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Window "Window position on screen"

You can specify ScriptLauncher window positions with the -WINDOW command:

    @{b}-WINDOW  xposition  yposition  [altxposition  [altyposition]]@{ub}

where

    xposition	  =  The x coordinate of the window (distance from the left
		     side).

    yposition	  =  The y coordinate of the window (distance from the top).

    altxposition  =  The x coordinate of the window when you click the zoom
		     gadget. If not specified, this defaults to the value of
		     xposition.

    altyposition  =  The y coordinate of the window when you click the zoom
		     gadget. If not specified, this defaults to the value of
		     yposition.

xposition and altxposition can be specified as either a numeric value or one
of the special keywords LEFT, CENTER (or CENTRE), or RIGHT. yposition and
altyposition can be specified as either a numeric value or one of the special
keywords TOP, CENTER (or CENTRE), or BOTTOM.

ScriptLauncher will adjust the window position before opening it so that it is
totally visible on the screen. Specifying a window coordinate that is too large
has the same effect as positioning the window to the right or bottom of the
screen.

All four values default to zero for the main window, meaning that the window
will be opened at the top left of the screen. If -WINDOW, is not specified
for a new window, ScriptLauncher uses the previous window's -WINDOW values.

Examples:

    -WINDOW  right 0		 The window will be adjusted to open at the right
				 side of the screen at the top. The alternate
				 window position associated with the zoom gadget
				 is the same as the initial position.

    -WINDOW  0 25 center bottom  The window will be opened on the left side of
				 the screen (X=0), 25 pixels down. If you click
				 the zoom gadget, the window will move to the
				 bottom center of the screen.

Of course, you can drag the window anywhere you want once it's open, and under
OS4, that can be partially off-screen if you have allowed off-screen window
dragging.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Wtitle "Window title"

You can specify the title for a ScriptLauncher window with the -WTITLE command:

    @{b}-WTITLE  windowtitle@{ub}

where

    windowtitle  =  A character string for a ScriptLauncher window title. If
		    not specified, the title will be blank. This is true for
		    the main window and any additional windows specified.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Wbkgd "Window background color"

You can specify the background color for a ScriptLauncher window with the
-WBKGD command:
@{b}
    -WBKGD  bkgdcolor
@{ub}
where

    bkgdcolor	 =  The name of the @{"color" LINK Color} to use for the window's background.
		    The color must be defined prior to this point.

If -WBKGD is not specified for the main window, ScriptLauncher uses color 0
for the window's background. If -WBKGD is not specified for a new window,
ScriptLauncher uses the previous window's -WBKGD color.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Screen "Public screen to open windows on"

You can specify the public screen where ScriptLauncher's windows will open with
the -SCREEN command:

    @{b}-SCREEN  pubscreenname@{ub}

where

    pubscreenname  =  The name of the public screen on which to open. If not
		      specified, it defaults to "Workbench".

This is a global command and should appear only once in the configuration file.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Font "Specify a font to use for button labels"

You can specify a font to use for button labels with the -FONT command:
@{b}
    -FONT  [fontlabel]	fontname  fontsize  [B|I|U]
@{ub}
where

    fontlabel =  An optional label or tag for this font. The label can appear in
		 @{"-TYPE" link Type} and @{"-BUTTON" link Button} commands. See below for further explanation.

    fontname  =  The name of the font to use.

    fontsize  =  The size of the font.

    B	      =  Use the @{b}BOLD@{ub} attribute of the font.

    I	      =  Use the @{i}ITALIC @{ui}attribute of the font.

    U	      =  Use the @{u}UNDERLINE@{uu} attribute of the font.

This is a global command and does not pertain to an individual window.

You can combine B, I, and U in a string to add together multiple attributes.
For example, "BU" would cause the text to be @{b}@{u}bold and underlined@{plain}.

Example:

    -FONT  'Bitstream Vera Sans.font' 13 B

ScriptLauncher will use the Bitstream Vera Sans font in 13 points, bold face.
Note that we had to use apostrophes because the font name has embedded spaces.

If no -FONT is specified at all, ScriptLauncher uses the screen's default font.

In order to maintain compatibility with version 1.0 of ScriptLauncher, you are
not required to specify a font label (they didn't exist in version 1.0). If you
omit it, ScriptLauncher will construct a label for the font in the form "fontX',
where 'X' is a decimal number starting at 1, and incrementing for each unlabelled
font you include. Normally you will want to label each font so that it can be
referred to by button types and/or individual buttons. Here is an example of
font labels:

    -font  courier.font 15 b		 <- receives the label 'font1'
    -font  f1  diamond.font 12		 <- receives the label 'f1'
    -font  f2  topaz.font 11 i		 <- receives the label 'f2'
    -font  helvetica.font 13		 <- receives the label 'font2'
@ENDNODE

@NODE Color "Define a color to use"

You can define a color to ScriptLauncher using the -COLOR command:
@{b}
    -COLOR  colorname  red,green,blue

    -COLOR  colorname  $rrggbb

    -COLOR  colorname  PEN  pennum@{ub}

This is a global command and does not pertain to an individual window.

You may also specify this command as "-COLOUR".

The first two formats are for defining a color by its red, green, and blue
components. ScriptLauncher uses the graphics.library call ObtainBestPen to
find a pen to use for the color. The third format tells ScriptLauncher to use
a specific pen for a given color. You are responsible to make sure that pen
writes in that color.

where

    colorname	    =  The name of the color. This can appear in @{"-TYPE" LINK Type},
		       @{"-BORDER" LINK Border}, @{"-WBKGD" LINK Wbkgd}, and @{"-BUTTON" Link Button} commands. Color names
		       are case-insensitive.

    red,green,blue  =  Three values representing the color's red, green, and
		       blue components. Each value must be 0-255, separated
		       by commas. Don't put spaces between the values.

    $rrggbb	    =  A hexadecimal color value representing the color's red,
		       green, and blue components. Six hex digits must be
		       specified. Each two digits must be in the range 00-FF.
		       Letters A-F need not be capitalized.

    PEN punnum	    =  A specific pen number to use for this color.

Examples:

    -COLOR  red  204,28,28		 A medium shade of red.

    -COLOR  red  $CC1C1C		 The same shade of red, in hexadecimal.

    -COLOR  'light green' 100,212,100    A light green color. We have to use
					 quotes because of the embedded space.

    -COLOR  yellow PEN 5		 Pen # 5 of the screen's palette, which
					 may (or may not) be yellow.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Type "Define a type of button"

You can define a type of button using the -TYPE command:

    @{b}-TYPE  typename  unselectedcolor  selectedcolor  textcolor  [fontlabel]@{ub}

where

    typename	     =	The name of this type of button. Type names are
			case-insensitive.

    unselectedcolor  =	The name of the background color of the button
			when it is unselected.

    selectedcolor    =	The name of the background color of the button
			when it is selected (clicked). This can, of course,
			be the same as unselectedcolor for no color change
			when clicked.

    textcolor	     =	The name of the text color for the button's label.

    fontlabel	     =	The @{"label" link Font} of the font to be used for this type of button.
			If not specified, it defaults to the first font specified.
			If no fonts are specified, it defaults to the screen's
			default font.

This is a global command and does not pertain to an individual window.

All three color names must be specified in the -TYPE command, and must be
defined prior to this point with @{"-COLOR" Link Color}.

Examples:

    -TYPE  APP	blue  cyan  black  f2	 A button type called "APP" which will
					 be blue with black text written with
					 font 'f2'. When the button is clicked
					 on, it will turn cyan.

    -TYPE  UTIL  tan  orange  white	 A button type called "UTIL" which will
					 be tan with white text written with the
					 first font specified. When the button
					 is clicked on, it will turn orange.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Button "Define a button and its script"

You can define a button to ScriptLauncher using the -BUTTON command:

    @{b}-BUTTON  buttonname  typename  [COLOR colorname]  [FONT fontlabel]  [outputspec]@{ub}

where

    buttonname	=  The label for this button. Labels are case-sensitive.
		   ScriptLauncher will try to center the button's label
		   both horizontally and vertically.

    typename	=  The name of a @{"type" LINK Type} of button. The type must be defined
		   prior to this point.

    colorname	=  The name of an override @{"color" link Color} for the button's label, used in
		   place of the text color associated with the button type. "COLOR"
		   can also be spelled "COLOUR". If not given, the color
		   associated with the button's type will be used.

    fontlabel	=  The @{"label" link Font} of the font to be used for this button, in place
		   of the normal font associated with the button type. If not
		   given, the font associated with the button's type will be
		   used.

    outputspec	=  An optional output specification for this button's script.
		   It should be of the form:

		   CON:x/y/width/height/title/options

		   Consult your AmigaDOS documentation for details on its
		   parameters. If outputspec is not specified, the script
		   does not have an output window. It's usually only needed
		   for a button that runs some AmigaDOS commands from C:
		   where you want to see the results.

The parameters after the typename parameter are optional and can be specified in
any order. The keywords "COLOR" and "FONT" identify the optional override color
and font. If a parameter follows the typename and is not preceded by "COLOR" or
"FONT", ScriptLauncher assumes that this is the output specification.  This allows
for compatibility with version 1.0 configuration files.

ScriptLauncher will lay out buttons in the window one after the other, in an
array. This array will either be filled in column by column, if you have
asked for vertical orientation in the @{"-DIMS" LINK Dims} command, or be filled in row by
row, if you have asked for horizontal orientation in the @{"-DIMS" LINK Dims} command.
Once it has filled up a page of buttons (equal to the number of rows * the
number of columns), ScriptLauncher automatically starts a new page for the
next button. You can use @{"-NEWROW" link Newrow}, @{"-NEWCOL" link Newcol}, and @{"-PAGE" link Page} to alter the button
layout.

Examples:

    -BUTTON  Unarc  UTIL	This button is labeled "Unarc", and button type
				UTIL specifies what colors and font it will use.

    -BUTTON  IBrowse  APP	This button is labeled "IBrowse", and button type
				APP specifies what colors and font it will use.

On the lines following the -BUTTON command, you can enter the button's script.
The script continues until the next line that begins with a '-'. Blank lines
and comment lines are ignored and are not stored as part of the script.

Script examples:

    -button Unarc UTIL
    cd sys:Tools
    Unarc Work:Downloads RAM:

This button is labeled "Unarc" as above, and will execute a two-line script
which CDs to "sys:Tools" and executes the "Unarc" utility. No separate output
window will open: Unarc is expected to open its own window.

    -button 'WORK-Usage' Shell CON:0/23/400/100//Close Color red
    stack 50000
    cd Work:
    Usage Downloads
    Usage brief

This button is labeled "WORK-Usage" and uses button type "Shell". The label
will appear in the override color "red". When clicked, it sets up a stack of
50000 bytes, CDs to "Work:", and does a couple of "usage" commands. The output
will go to a window on the Workbench screen, which will have a close gadget.

Special @{"script commands" LINK Scrcmds} can be specified in a script. These can perform such
actions as @{"changing" LINK CmdPage} the page of buttons that is displayed, conditionally
@{"including" LINK CmdIf} lines from the script based on use of the ALT, CTL, and AMIGA keys,
@{"opening" Link Openwin} and @{"closing" Link Closewin} ScriptLauncher windows, and @{"quitting" LINK CmdQuit} ScriptLauncher.
Script commands are recognized by an '=' in column 1 of the line.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Empty "Define an empty space"

You can define an empty button slot with the -EMPTY command:

    @{b}-EMPTY@{ub}

There are no parameters. ScriptLauncher will allocate a space the size of a
single button, which will be filled with the window's @{"background color" LINK Wbkgd}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Newrow "Start a new row of buttons"

You can cause ScriptLauncher to start a new row of buttons with the -NEWROW
command:

    @{b}-NEWROW@{ub}

There are no parameters. ScriptLauncher will start laying out buttons in the
next row, skipping the rest of the current row. If it is already positioned
at the start of a new row, this command will do nothing.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Newcol "Start a new column of buttons"

You can cause ScriptLauncher to start a new column of buttons with the -NEWCOL
command:

    @{b}-NEWCOL@{ub}

There are no parameters. ScriptLauncher will start laying out buttons in the
next column, skipping the rest of the current column. If it is already
positioned at the start of a new column, this command will do nothing.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Page "Start a new page of buttons"

You can cause ScriptLauncher to start a new page of buttons with the -PAGE
command:

    @{b}-PAGE@{ub}

There are no parameters. ScriptLauncher will start laying out buttons on a
new page, skipping the rest of the current page. If it is already positioned
at the start of a new page, this command will do nothing.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Newwin "Define an additional window"

You can define an additional window with the -NEWWIN command:

    @{b}-NEWWIN  windowname  [DEFER]@{ub}

where

    windowname	=  An internal name for the window. This can be used in @{"=OPENWIN" link Openwin}
		   and @{"=CLOSEWIN" link Closewin} script commands.

    DEFER	=  If specified, ScriptLauncher will not open this window at
		   startup, but only on demand via the above script commands.
		   Do not specify DEFER if you want the window to be opened
		   immediately when ScriptLauncher starts up.

The new window will inherit all the attributes of the preceding window, with the
exception of the window title, which defaults to blank. On subsequent lines of the
configuration file, you can change the new window's attributes by using commands
such as @{"-WINDOW" link Window}, @{"-DIMS" link Dims}, @{"-BSIZE" link Bsize}, etc. as listed under @{"Configuration File Setup" link Config}.
Following these window attribute commands, you would begin to define the buttons
and associated scripts for this new window.
@ENDNODE


@NODE Include "Read another file of configuration commands"

You can tell ScriptLauncher to include another command file by using the
-INCLUDE command:

    @{b}-INCLUDE filename@{ub}

where

    filename  =  name of the command file to include. This should either be
		 in the same path as the main configuration file, or be
		 fully qualified.

-INCLUDEs cannot be nested.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Comment "Include a comment line"

Comments may be specified anywhere in the configuration file with the '--'
command:

    @{b}-- This is a comment@{ub}

The '--' must appear in the first two columns of the line.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Scrcmds "Script Commands"

Button scripts may have commands embedded in them which are executed when you
click on that button. These commands are recognized by an '=' in column 1 of
the line.

The following script commands are recognized by ScriptLauncher:

   @{"=QUIT    " LINK CmdQuit}  Quit ScriptLauncher after starting this script
   @{"=PAGE    " LINK CmdPage}  Display a different page of buttons
   @{"=MOD     " LINK CmdMod}  Prompt for a modification of this script line
   @{"=IF      " LINK CmdIf}  Conditionally include this script line based on key pressed
   @{"=REQ     " LINK CmdReq}  Show a requester and get a response value
   @{"=FREQ    " LINK CmdFreq}  Show an ASL file requester and get file & path names
   @{"=DREQ    " LINK CmdFreq}  Show an ASL directory requester and get path name
   @{"=OPENWIN " LINK Openwin}  Open a ScriptLauncher window
   @{"=CLOSEWIN" LINK Closewin}  Close a ScriptLauncher window

Note that some script commands set @{b}variables@{ub} which can be used in the script
that is built. ScriptLauncher variables are identified by a leading @{b}'\\'@{ub}
character. The variable name follows the '\\' and is case-insensitive. The
name can be composed only of letters (a-z or A-Z) and digits (0-9). All
variables are cleared each time ScriptLauncher begins to build a script when
a button is clicked.
@ENDNODE

@NODE CmdQuit "Script Command to Quit ScriptLauncher"

You can tell ScriptLauncher to quit when a script is run with the =QUIT
script command:

    @{b}=QUIT@{ub}

There are no parameters. ScriptLauncher will quit running after it starts
executing the script in which =QUIT occurs. If you are overriding the script
by shift-clicking the button and you click "Cancel script" in the override
window, ScriptLauncher will not execute the =QUIT command.

You might use this to relaunch ScriptLauncher after editing its configuration
file, like so:

    -BUTTON 'Restart' SPECIAL
    cd sys:Tools  (or wherever you put the program)
    ScriptLauncher myconfig
    =QUIT

This button is labeled "Restart" of type "SPECIAL". It will execute
ScriptLauncher from sys:Tools, and after starting the script, the previous
ScriptLauncher process will quit. Of course you could just pick @{"Restart" LINK UseMenu} from
the Project menu to do the same thing, but the above might be useful if you
want to run ScriptLauncher with a different configuration file.
@ENDNODE

@NODE CmdPage "Script Command to display a different page of buttons"

A different page of buttons can be displayed with the =PAGE script command:

    @{b}=PAGE [+|-]n@{ub}

where

    +	indicates to go forward 'n' pages from the current page.

    -	indicates to go backward 'n' pages from the current page.

    n	indicates the page number. It is an absolute page number if neither
	"+" nor "-" are used.

ScriptLauncher will evaluate the new page number and display the new page
of buttons. It will "wrap around" after the last page or before the first
page. That is, if you ask for a page beyond the last page, it will display
the first page. If you ask for a page before the first page (with "-n"), it
will display the last page.

Examples:

    -BUTTON 'Page 3' SPECIAL
    =PAGE 3

This button is labeled "Page 3" of type "SPECIAL". It will cause page 3
of buttons to be shown, if three pages worth have been defined, otherwise
it will show page 1.

    -BUTTON 'Previous' plain
    =PAGE -1

This button is labeled "Previous" of type "plain". It will cause the previous
page of buttons to be shown. If showing page 1, it will show the last page.

Although I can't think of a reason for it, =PAGE does not have to be used
alone as in the examples above, but could appear in a regular script with
other AmigaDOS or script commands.
@ENDNODE

@NODE CmdMod "Script Command to prompt for script line modification"

You can use the =MOD script command to force a script line to prompt for
modification when the button is clicked:

    @{b}=MOD line to be modified@{ub}

The script line to be modified should immediately follow "=MOD" - no spaces
are necessary (but could be put in for readability).

The modification prompt that appears is the same requester window that
appears when you @{"shift-click" LINK UseMod} a button.

In the modification requester window, you can choose the same four options
as discussed under @{"Modifying scripts" LINK UseMod}:

  -  you can modify the line presented (if you wish)
  -  you can modify the line presented (if you wish) and make this the
     last modification prompt
  -  you can insert a new line at the current point in the script
  -  you can cancel the script and not run it at all

If you click "Run script" in the window, any further script lines that are
prefixed with "=MOD" will @{b}not@{ub} prompt you for modification.

Note also that ScriptLauncher shows you which line of the script is being
modified in the requester window title bar, saying "LINE x OF y". These
are line numbers of the original script, @{b}not@{ub} the "x'th" line of "y" being
modified. If it says "Line 1 of 3", that means you have a three-line script,
and you are looking at line 1, not the first of three modifications.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Openwin "Script Command to open a ScriptLauncher window"

Use the =OPENWIN script command to open a window you have defined to ScriptLauncher:

    @{b}=OPENWIN  windowname@{ub}

where

    windowname	=  the internal name for the window, as specified in the
		   @{"-NEWWIN" Link Newwin} command, or the literal 'MAIN' to refer to the
		   main (first) window.

ScriptLauncher will ignore the =OPENWIN command if the specified window is
not defined or if it is already open. No error message appears.

For windows defined with the DEFER option of the -NEWWIN command, =OPENWIN
is the only way to open the window.

See the @{"=CLOSEWIN" Link Closewin} command for an example of opening and closing windows
in a script.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Closewin "Script Command to ›close a ScriptLauncher window"

Use the =CLOSEWIN script command to close a ScriptLauncher window:

    @{b}=CLOSEWIN  windowname@{ub}

where

    windowname	=  the internal name for the window, as specified in the
		   @{"-NEWWIN" Link Newwin} command, or the literal 'MAIN' to refer to the
		   main (first) window.

ScriptLauncher will ignore the =CLOSEWIN command if the specified window is
not defined or if it is already closed. No error message appears. If you
close the main window, the menu item @{"Reopen main window" Link UseMenu} will be unghosted,
allowing you to reopen it. Alternatively you can use @{"=OPENWIN" Link Openwin} to reopen
the main window in a script.

The following example illustrates opening and closing windows in a script.
It defines a button in the main window which will close the main window and
open a minimal window in the lower right corner of the screen with a single
button in it:

    -button 'SHRINK' button-type        This button will be defined in the main
    =openwin little			window. It will close the main window
    =closewin main			and open a window called 'little'.
					(Fill in a defined button type.)

    ----------------------------
    ----------------------------

    -newwin little defer		This defines a new window called 'little'
    -dims 1 1 vert			which is not automatically opened. It
    -bsize 60 14			appears in the bottom right of the screen.
    -window bottom right

    -button 'Reopen' button-type        This single button appears in the 'little'
    =openwin main			window. It closes the 'little' window and
    =closewin little			reopens the main window.

@ENDNODE

@NODE CmdIf "Script Command to conditionally include a script line"

You can use the =IF script command to conditionally include a script line:

    @{b}=IF (ALT|CTL|AMIGA|NALT|NCTL|NAMIGA|NONE)line to be included@{ub}

where

    ALT     =  include this line if either ALT key is pressed.
    CTL     =  include this line if either CTL key is pressed.
    AMIGA   =  include this line if either AMIGA key is pressed.
    NALT    =  include this line if neither ALT key is pressed.
    NCTL    =  include this line if neither CTL key is pressed.
    NAMIGA  =  include this line if neither AMIGA key is pressed.
    NONE    =  include this line if none of the above keys is pressed.

The script line to be conditionally included should immediately follow the
parenthesized condition - no spaces are necessary.

The SHIFT key is not included as a modifier key in the above list, because
ScriptLauncher uses the SHIFT key to allow line-by-line @{"modification" LINK UseMod} of the
script being built.

Examples:

    =IF(ALT)cd WORK:            The line "cd WORK:" will be copied into the
				script being built if an ALT key is pressed
				when you click the script's button.

    =IF(NONE)avail flush        The line "avail flush" will be copied into the
				script being built if no ALT, CTL, or AMIGA
				key is pressed when you click the script's
				button.

    -BUTTON Example UTIL	This button of type UTIL will have "cd SYS:"
    =IF(NONE)cd SYS:            in the script if no key is pressed when the
    =IF(ALT) cd DH1:            button is clicked; will have "cd DH1:" in the
    =IF(CTL) cd DH2:            script if an ALT key is pressed; will have
				"cd DH2:" in the script if a CTL key is
				pressed; and if an AMIGA key is pressed, no
				"cd" command line will be copied to the script.
				Be aware that if both ALT and CTL are pressed,
				the script will have both "cd DH1:" and "cd DH2:"!

It is possible to stack multiple =IF commands together to produce an "AND"
relationship test of keys pressed:

    =IF(alt)=IF(nctl)dir T:     The line "dir T:" will be copied into the
				script being built if an ALT key is pressed
				and neither CTL key is pressed when you
				click the script's button.

At the present time there is no way to specify an "OR" relationship test
in a single =IF command.

Note also that although ScriptLauncher checks both AMIGA keys in the =IF
logic, you really can only use the right AMIGA key - the OS reserves the
left AMIGA key for its own use, and (at least in my tests) a left-AMIGA
click of a button does not run a script at all.
@ENDNODE

@NODE CmdReq "Script Command to show a requester"

You can have ScriptLauncher present a requester with the =REQ script command:

    @{b}=REQ  title  prompttext  buttontext  [returnvalues]@{ub}

where

    title	  =  requester window title

    prompttext	  =  text for the body of the requester. If you want more than
		     one line, separate the lines with a vertical bar (|).
		     For double spacing, put two vertical bars in a row.

    buttontext	  =  labels for the button gadgets of the requester. You can
		     make multiple buttons by separating the labels with a
		     vertical bar (|).

    returnvalues  =  return values corresponding to the button gadgets. You
		     should have as many values here, separated by vertical
		     bars (|), as you have button gadgets. If there are less
		     values, the missing values default to a null string. If
		     this parameter is missing, it defaults to the buttontext
		     parameter.

=REQ should appear on a line by itself. If the title, prompttext, or
buttontext parameters are missing, the requester is not displayed, and
the =REQ script line is output to the script file unchanged. If you don't
want to have a requester title, make the title a single space ' ' rather
than a null string ''.

ScriptLauncher will display the requester and get the user response. The
return value corresponding to the button pressed is placed into a variable
which can be used in subsequent script lines. The variable name is of the
form @{b}\\Rx@{ub}, where x starts at 1 for the first =REQ command, and is incremented
by 1 for each subsequent =REQ in the same script. The first time you use =REQ,
the variable \\R1 is created, the second time \\R2, and so on.

It is possible to have some null values in the returnvalues parameter -
see the second example below. You probably don't want to have any null
buttontext values, however.

Examples:

    -button Example SHELL con:0/0/500/200//Close
    =REQ 'Question' 'What dir info do you want?' 'Names only|All info' 'dir|list'
    \\r1 ram:

This button would present a requester with two buttons, "Names only" and
"All info". Clicking on the first button would set the variable \\R1 to
"dir"; clicking on the second button would set it to "list". The variable
is then used to build a script line to show the RAM: directory via either
the DIR or LIST command.

    -button Example2 SPECIAL con:0/0/500/200//Close
    =REQ 'Shell setup' 'Select stack size' 'Default|50K|100K' '|50000|100000'
    stack \\r1

This button would present a requester with three buttons, "Default", "50K",
and "100K". The first return value, corresponding to Default, is a null
string. The second value is "50000" and the third is "100000". The script
that is built performs a stack command as follows -

		  Button "Default"    ->    stack
		  Button "50K"        ->    stack 50000
		  Button "100K"       ->    stack 100000

    -button Example3 SPECIAL
    =REQ 'Choose one' 'What type of ASSIGNs|do you want to list?' 'VOLS|DIRS|DEVICES'
    assign \\r1

This button would present a requester with three buttons, "VOLS", "DIRS",
and "DEVICES". Since there is no returnvalue parameter, the button labels
double as return values, and one of them will be assigned to variable \\R1.
The script that is built does an ASSIGN command with one of the three values.
@ENDNODE

@NODE CmdFreq "Script Commands to show an ASL requester"

You can have ScriptLauncher ask for a file or directory name via an ASL
requester with the =FREQ and =DREQ script commands:

    @{b}=FREQ [start-dir [title [pattern] ] ]@{ub}

    @{b}=DREQ [start-dir [title [pattern] ] ]@{ub}

where

    start-dir  =  initial drawer or directory to display; if not specified,
		  defaults to blank

    title      =  ASL window title; if not specified, defaults to
		  "Select File to Open"

    pattern    =  file pattern; if not specified, defaults to "#?".

These two script commands cause ScriptLauncher to show an ASL requester.
=FREQ shows a regular file requester, and =DREQ shows a directory requester.
Parameters are positional, so if you want to specify a window title or file
pattern, you have to specify also a starting directory name. =FREQ/=DREQ
should appear on a line by itself.

The filename or directoryname from the ASL requester is put into two variables
which can be used in subsequent script lines. The variable names are shown
below:

    \\Fx  =  the full file or directory name with the path (x = 1,2,3,...)
    \\Nx  =  just the file or directory name (x = 1,2,3,...)

The first time you use =FREQ/=DREQ, the resulting filename will be placed in
variables '\\f1' and '\\n1'; the second time in the same script you use
=FREQ/=DREQ, the filename is placed in '\\f2' and '\\n2', and so on. You can
use both '\\f1' and '\\n1' to refer to different pieces of the filename
resulting from the same ASL requester - both variables are stored.

Typically you might use this script command to request a file via ASL for a
command that expects a file name argument only on the command line and does
not prompt for it, as suggested in the fictitious example below:

Example:

    -button CLIonly shell
    =FREQ RAM:
    CLIcommand \\f1 value2 value3

This defines a button called 'CLIonly' of type SHELL. It first requests a file
via an ASL requester and records the resulting filename in variables '\\f1'
(with path) and '\\n1' (without path). On the next line, it builds a script
line to execute something called 'CLIcommand' and substitutes for the value of
variable \\f1. If you chose a file named "mytext", the script line would
appear as:

    CLIcommand mytext value2 value3

Note that ScriptLauncher does not automatically put quotes around filenames,
so if your filename could possibly have embedded spaces in it, you would be
better off defining the above button with this script line:

    CLIcommand "\\f1" value2 value3

resulting in:

    CLIcommand "mytext" value2 value3

Note finally that if you cancel the ASL requester, ScriptLauncher aborts the
entire script.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Author "Author Information"

ScriptLauncher is written by Joe Howard (jhoward@icdc.com).

I had been using CliVa as a program launch tool under OS3.x, but when I
got an AmigaOne and OS4.0, CliVa looked kind of dated and had problems
with script overrides. OS4.0 comes with AmiDock which I tried out, but I
prefer a button-based program launcher to an icon-based one. CliVa is a
good tool, but it hasn't been updated in many years. Its requesters look
old-fashioned, it has some arcane syntax, and its button coloring is
limited to (I think) 64 pens. Not only that, but you have to use specific
pen numbers with CliVa which have to be set up in your palette. With OS3.0
and up, we have been moving toward dynamic pen allocation with ObtainBestPen
and such. In addition, script overrides in CliVa (with the shift key) did
not appear to work at all under OS4.0. Apparently the override requester is
somehow opened off-screen and there's no way to drag it back on screen. So,
I decided to try to write a replacement program launcher that's more
up-to-date. Besides, it never hurts to have more than one choice for any type
of software. Thus ScriptLauncher resembles CliVa overall, but I have rethought
its features and come up with (I hope) more readable syntax for the
configuration file.
@ENDNODE

@NODE History "Notes on various versions"

 V1.0  July 2, 2005   The initial version. I've been doing Amiga programming
		      since 1991 but have never released any software to the
		      Amiga community. I initially wrote ScriptLauncher for
		      myself (how selfish :-) but it occurred to me that
		      other Amigans might find it useful as well. I would
		      like to continue to enhance ScriptLauncher with new
		      features as long as they are worthwhile. Although I
		      have my own ideas for future enhancements, any
		      suggestions are welcome.

 V1.1  June 8, 2006   I've been running this version of ScriptLauncher for a
		      number of months, but have been holding off releasing
		      it until I had added another feature or two. I intended
		      to release it much sooner than this, but seeing as I
		      haven't added any new features for a while and I'm
		      involved in other stuff right now, I'm releasing this
		      version with what it's got. There are no bug fixes in
		      it, since no one's reported any bugs (can this be?).
		      (Well, actually, there is one extremely minor fix that
		      you probably never noticed in the override window.)
@ENDNODE

@NODE V11new "What's New in Version 1.1"

Here's what's new in version 1.1 of ScriptLauncher:

  -  ScriptLauncher can now have multiple @{"windows" link Newwin} of buttons open at once. The
     windows can either open when ScriptLauncher starts or be opened later via
     the @{"=OPENWIN" link Openwin} script command. Each window can have its own attributes such as
     button size and layout. Scripts can also close windows via the @{"=CLOSEWIN" link Closewin}
     script command.

  -  ScriptLauncher allows you to use multiple @{"fonts" link Font} for button labels. The font
     is normally associated with the button @{"type" link Type}, but can be overridden for each
     individual button.

  -  The button's label @{"color" link Button} can also be overridden for each individual button.

  -  You can now @{"insert lines" link UseMod} in a script when shift-clicking the script's button.

  -  You can use the special keywords LEFT, RIGHT, CENTER (or CENTRE), TOP, and
     BOTTOM to specify a window's @{"position" link Window}.

@ENDNODE

